segments.text: one two one two one two testing one two one two one two friday afternoon uh february the 9th have the honor and pleasure of interviewing dr john klater we're in the evans library to begin with introduce yourself
tell us all about you and your family before you came to A&M.
Where'd you grow up?
What did mom and dad do?
How long did y'all live there?
Where'd you go to high school and so forth?
Well, my name is John Claytor.
I was born in Denver, Colorado March 4th of 1951 when dad was a surgical resident there in Denver.
Dad came to West Texas in 1958 to go into
private general surgical practice.
I have three brothers, Mike, class of 68, myself of number two, Tim's class of 74, and Dan's class of 78.
All four of us were in the core, well, two of us were in the core and two were in the band.
And older brother Mike is a Ph.D. electrical engineer.
I'm a veterinarian.
Tim is an orthopedist in Buffalo, New York, or Rochester, New York, and Danny is a dentist down in Montrose, Colorado.
Father was, as I said, was a general surgeon.
Mother was a Nebraska farm girl, became a nurse.
And we lived in Midland all the way through late 50s through the 60s.
I came to A&M in the fall of 1968 after graduating from Midland Lee High School.
All right.
So the question of why did you come to A&M?
Very simple.
I came to A&M.
That's where my older brother had gone.
Looking back on it, parents certainly encouraged it because of the discipline of the Corps and probably because it was the cheapest place they could send us, but we didn't realize that at the time.
When my older brother had come to A&M in 64, we really didn't know what A&M was about.

He was an engineering major and he was accepted at Rice and at Texas, but engineers in Midland told my parents that A&M was the best place to go for engineering because they taught practical problem solving, not theory.
So Mike was sent off to A&M.
CORE was still compulsory, and he didn't know any better, so letters that came home didn't register much.
They said it was tough, but that's just the way it is.
He lost weight and did fine.
I didn't see him until Thanksgiving, I guess, of his freshman year.
And took him back, I guess, on Sunday after Thanksgiving.
That's the first time I'd seen A&M, and I

kind of hard to fall in love with a place that looked like truly like Leavenworth Federal Penitentiary but it was the neatest thing in the world to me at that time and it was about commitment and growing up in the military and it's what I wanted to do so from that moment on I was really ed up with going to A&M being in the Corps.
And you didn't seriously consider any other place?
No my
Grade school teacher, second and third grade teacher, Mrs. Woodruff in Sam Houston Elementary, was married to the president of the West Texas Princeton Club.
And they had wanted me to go to Princeton in the worst way, and I had the grades to get in and their support.
And I think I broke her heart when I told her that as a senior in high school that, no, I wanted to go to A&M.
And no, never really looked at anywhere else and I certainly didn't want to go to Austin.
And you visited the first time that Thanksgiving.
Did you walk around on the campus much?
I did.
Of course it was a different campus than it is today.
In fact, we even spent the night at the MSC.
Came home Monday but got to walk around as I recall and
I mean, I'm a high school freshman and a year younger than the rest of my class, and I've got total strangers coming up and saying howdy and asking if they could help.
And I'm not a country kid, but at the same time, they were pretty outgoing.
It was pretty neat.
And I was very impressed with the Corps.
A little overtaken, and my brother was a freshman at the time, so that wasn't a great time to be maybe in the Corps of Cadets, but it still impressed me.
When you came to enroll in the fall of 60.
Would have been the fall of 68.
Did you go to fish camp?
No, didn't.
It was, I don't know if it's compulsory now.
It wasn't then.
I didn't go.
I spent a summer working in the oil field to make money for college.
How did you get here that fall?
My mother brought me.
And dad was busy with practice, so he couldn't come.
What did you bring?
Knowing a little bit about the Corps and what was required, I brought a footlocker, and that was it.
I had my civilian clothes, the uniforms you pick up, but everything I had could be packed into a footlocker, and that's how I went off to college.
And you drove to where?
We drove from Midland, Texas, straight to College Station, and since we knew where the Corps dorms were, we went and checked in, and they told us what
dormitory to go to, and mom, kind of interesting, she understood the drill a whole lot better than I did, and she stayed at the car.
She didn't have to see her baby off, but another freshman came out, a guy named Carl Alexander from New Orleans, Louisiana.
His dad was vice president of Texaco for the Caribbean and South America.
We ended up rooming together for a semester.
And that's another story, but this fish came out in a t-shirt and blue jeans and said, hi, I'm Carl Alexander from New Orleans, Louisiana.
And I'd never heard anybody talk like that, but he grabbed one end of the footlocker and off we went.
And mom gave me a squeeze and that was it.
And it didn't dawn on me that I'd just been cast to the wolves.
your parents or anyone else give you any kind of final advice as you kind of broke away from home that fall?
It's an older gentleman that lives south of Jersey Street.
I guess it's George Bush Street now.
I believe last name was Callender.
They had little, they'd take girlfriends in on the weekends and whatnot.
People could stay down there a couple blocks south of the school and he told me
around that time period.
It wasn't on that trip, but it was perhaps right before, maybe a previous visit right before that, no, I guess it was that same weekend.
He said, if you ever get your tail in a crack, give me a call.
And it took me a little while to figure out what he was talking about, but I never did, but he was a wonderful old gentleman that had seen generations of Aggies come through College Station.
All right, and you had no second thoughts at all
when mom drove away or anything like that.
You knew that this is where you wanted to go.
That's what I wanted to do.
But I had been, with my older brother having gone through four years, and I'd been in College Station, been to TU football games, knew some of the guys that were in his outfit.
I thought I had some idea of how the system worked.
Now, that bubble was burst about two hours later when I ran into my first sophomore.
Describe that.
He was a sophomore from another outfit.
And I had just dropped my stuff off and had gone to the Memorial Student Center and came back around.
And there was a freshman doing push-ups over right next to the fence with Kyle Field.
And it was just that same afternoon.
And there were two sophomores there.
And one of them was named Emmons, and he was the one that was in charge.
The other one was named Wasaki.
And I remember that because we used to call him Mr. Wallsocket.
But they had a freshman down doing push-ups for whatever sin he'd committed.
And since I was a freshman, I was called in to participate.
Wasn't in my outfit, didn't have a thing to do with it, but I was there.
So I spent about an hour and a half over there until I couldn't do much more.
And my other fish buddy had thrown up on the sidewalk there in the sun, and then they let us go.
And then I decided that perhaps there was a little bit more to the Corps of Cadets than I realized.
And you were in what outfit?
I was in Squadron 6.
Did it have a nickname?
Savage 6.
Savage 6.
How did, do you know how you ended up in that outfit?
You had two outfits that were primarily pre-vet outfits.
And I declared pre-vet medicine as a preliminary major.
It was made up of ag majors and pre-vet students.
With C1 in the Army side and Squadron 6 on the Air Force side.
and B1 on the Army side being pre-vet outfits pretty much.
And in what dormitory?
Dorm 8 was the bottom floor.
And you ended up, how'd you get a roommate that first year?
Just, he walked in that night, and name was Mark Taylor from Houston, Texas, and Mark lasted one semester at A&M, and that was it.
Nice guy.
Did he, yeah.
You were talking about this roommate.
Mark Taylor, yes.
And I don't remember how or why Mark came to be in the Corps, but there were 56 of us that started, yeah, that was the fall of 68.
Anyway, 56 of us started in Squadron 6, and I believe eight of us graduated four years later.
about how many of those came back in the Corps the second year?
We, let's see, I think we returned a pretty large percentage.
There were only six sophomores above us
because the previous year, due to the class, it would have been the class of 71, their freshman year, there was an early football game.
It was going to be on national TV with SMU.
And in order to get the outfits and the freshmen whipped into shape, they really worked on them awful hard.
And I know squadron six was not the only one, but they lost a tremendous number of freshmen and only had six sophomores come back.
We returned
probably in excess of 20.
Describe how you and that fish old lady got acquainted and what was the room like and so forth.
Well, I'd gotten there first and my older brother told me that you always wanted the bottom bunk.
Nobody's, you know, you could get in and out easier and it was a little darker down there.
You got two desks, you got two closets, you don't have anything else.
It didn't really make any difference.
So I had my stuff on one side and he came in and

I he didn't much care so we just you do this do that okay and he was clueless he didn't know anything about the Corps of Cadets he just shown up and there he was and I didn't know a whole lot more so we didn't didn't have a whole lot to share that first first few weeks he was pre-vet and don't know whatever happened to him but he he decided A&M wasn't for him and he left it mid semester how did

you get your schedule of courses for that fall did you go through registration went through registration where was it and i don't remember g raleigh or uh sabisa i think i would think that it was not not at sabisa for me uh and it may have been i believe it was done during
a summer orientation.
I suspect that's when it was.
That's not clear.
I don't have a good memory of that.
But that's my recollection that I was pretty well set in my coursework when I showed up that fall.
I didn't have to stand in line to go to registration.
Do you describe what you recall of those first classes?
The first day of class.
Now, you're there in the Corps.
You're learning to drill.
You're learning to march.
We'd learn how to put your uniforms on, and they're going through things, and you don't know.

But I remember the first day of class when this same Carl Alexander, who was not my roommate, but the kid from New Orleans, it had a light rain that morning, and we're leaving for our first day of classes, and he heads down the quad with an umbrella.
And you don't do this when you're under military cover.
But he didn't know because he grew up in New Orleans High Society, and you never went outside without your umbrella.
And he made it all the way to the end of the quad before somebody realized this isn't right.
There wasn't something they couldn't put their finger on it, but they, it was, it was wild, uh, classes.
I had, uh, an honors algebra class, had a lady professor was quite good and thorough and no problems.
Uh, freshman chemistry.
I can remember sitting.
in freshman chemistry late that Monday morning and the professor saying, look to your left and look to your right.
You've heard it before, but I'll tell you that only one third of you will be here next semester for the second half of this course.
And we all kind of chuckled and that's exactly what it was.
I can remember trying to get to class
and having to whip out and meet upperclassmen and sometimes not being able to get to class because you'd hike off to the architecture building or to the MSC and you had a class in another building.
You couldn't leave that upperclassman or get away from him, so I remember that.
Any other classes you remember that fall or spring, that freshman year?
Well, Honors American History.
There was a Dr. Haskell Monroe.
And I can honestly say that it was probably, in many ways, the most challenging class.
Not necessarily the hardest, but it was the most challenging class I had because Dr. Monroe would frequently give me a hard time about being in the Corps.
Why don't you get out?
Why are you staying in?
I was in the Honors Colloquia.
It was a smaller American history class.
It's also the first class that somebody said, get a blue book and write down everything you know.
I don't care about your spelling or your handwriting or your punctuation or your grammar, but write down everything you know about this subject or that subject.
And he'd only give us a test with two or three subjects.
So these are things that some 30 years later you remember, 32 years later, you remember well.
And these are things that prepare you when
You're sitting in a boardroom at the Royal Veterinary College in London, England, and somebody wants you to tell what you have just seen of their college, and don't pull any punches.
And it was easy to do, and the first thing I thought was my blue book.
In that class were a group of sophomores and some freshmen, some that went on with me, maybe one or two to vet school, others to other professions.
One, Dr.
I believe it was Andy Anderson, who
you probably remember.
Was a sophomore at that time and has gone on to great things.
I believe he's a thoracic surgeon.
And a few others that have done things.
So it was an interesting group.
And what I hope was understandable when I was challenging people like you on the Corps is
are you doing what you want to do?
Have you thought it through?
If you haven't, do.
You've got a choice, make it.
That's right.
And it was an interesting, let's qualify that for the record.
This is the fall of 68.
It's the height of the Vietnam War.
In many ways, we felt like it was us against the rest of the world.
Right or wrong, we were in the military, and that's the way we felt.
During those first months, did you ever think about dropping out, going somewhere else?
I never did.
I had a girlfriend at Baylor, and you know, you miss seeing your girlfriend, but no other school held it for me.
I did find it harder than I expected.
It didn't kill me, but it was harder.
I lost a little weight.
I remember what it was like those first three weeks of waking up with a knot in my stomach.
Never had that experience in my life.
It was okay though, but I really didn't know this was it.
Nobody in Midland, Texas wanted to hear that I wanted to come home, so it was sink or swim.
And how often that fall did you communicate with family?
Letters or phone calls?
Probably weekly letters.
Long distance.
Phones cost money back then, so we didn't call much, but frequent letters back and forth.
My dad wasn't a letter writer.
Every once in a while he'd jot a little something down, but nice letters from home, care packages.
You remember those, especially as a freshman.

when, you know, we called it kush, but when cookies or popcorn or something came, or maybe cookies with popcorn packed around them, and it didn't take long, and you could figure out whose mothers were good at sending stuff and if it was going to be edible.
I had one guy that had a very wonderful, dutiful girlfriend that was the worst cook in the world.
And so, you know, that stuff we let the upperclassmen feast on.
You went to the dining hall, to Duncan.
What was the routine in your outfit in the dining hall?
Well, of course, we ate family style.
We blocked in.
We had our area to sit in, and we had assigned seats.

We would have either juniors or seniors on the row, the non-walking aisle where the support pillars were, then a freshman that would give meal service to them, then a sophomore, and then freshman again.
And the freshman on the end would run hot corner.
You would alternate between giving meal service

to a white belt or being on hot corner and that would change probably oh on a every other week basis uh... that sort of thing the uh... kids that ran hot corner would take the order from the waiters that came and the other freshmen were strictly to feed the and take care of the upperclassmen which uh... our commanding officer was from wall texas a big tall

German guy named George Schriever and George was about six foot six almost too tall to get an Air Force contract but just just barely made it big ugly scar-faced cotton farmer from Wall Texas and one of my fondest recollections about meal service was when it was raining it was early spring of my freshman year and somebody had stolen a fetal pig from the biology lab and
Keith Schwartz was the only Jewish kid we had in the outfit.
He only lasted two semesters, but he contrived to hang this fetal pig between his legs and made it all the way to chow underneath his raincoat.
Nobody could see it.
Even with formaldehyde, they didn't smell it.
We got it all the way in, and then they snuck it under the table.
to me and I placed it on our commanding officer's plate and cut it up and stuck a fork in it.
And needless to say, he didn't pay any attention to what he was eating until he nearly got it in his mouth.
And we paid a very heavy price for that, but it was worth it.
Now that's a superb Good Bull story.
The fetal pig that went to chow.
Were there cush questions at your table?
Every night.
Sample some of them for us.
You know, I'll tell you one.
We had to make up Aggie jokes.
We went through a period that we had to have a new Aggie joke or we couldn't eat.
We had guys getting old Polish joke books, bohunk joke books, whatever it took, joke books from relatives, anything they could find.
And the upperclassmen, we went through about a six-week period, didn't have a new Aggie joke.
We got turned away at the door.
We marched a child.
We turned away.
So that didn't take long, and we became very, very good at reciting Aggie jokes.
A Cush question that I got the other day, an example.
How many stars are there in the Texas flag?
I don't know.
Sure you do.
In the Texas flag?
Not the American flag, just the Texas flag.
Oh, what?
No, there's two.
There's one on each side.
That's right.
And if you had said two, he'd said, no, it's one.
It goes all the way through.
You can't win on a cush question.
See, there's no answer to a cush question.
And the reason they have a cush question is because the upperclassman that asks, you're betting on the food.
And if it's something that he wants, okay, it's a double or nothing deal.
If you get it right, it's yours.
If you lose, it's mine.
So that they ask a question for which they know whatever answer you give, they're not going to accept it.
Now, I'll take cush questions to another level.
Had one upperclassman
named Bill Hall, he was our first sergeant, and Bill did not like cobbler.
Didn't like the crumbly cob, it was great, but he didn't like it.

And if we ever ate a meal that his roommate wasn't there, Rick Fitzhugh, Bill would ask, because he loved to get one step ahead of the sophomores before the cush questions, and he would say, Fish Jones,

which piece is yours and if you ever asked a freshman which piece was his he was to take his fist and bury it in the middle of the cobbler pot just like this one sir and cawap and the stuff flew all over the table hit the sophomores hit the freshmen but they couldn't do anything because that was legal so they didn't get their cush and they got a dirty uniform instead now the freshmen usually paid for it later on but
That was a good bull.
Lots of campusology, lots of questions.
All the nicknames of the food, did you ever get into trouble with any of the food nicknames or the chow hall slang back home that you forgot what you were about to say?
Well, mayonnaise was called cum, you know, like an ejaculate.
And I sat there at home and I said, shoot the cum, please.
And my little brother looked at me and just, what are you talking about?
Mustard was baby, that was fine.
Blood, bull neck.
It was worse at my girlfriend's house because they had no clue.

her mother got a little upset that I referred to steak one night as bull neck not meaning to but she mistakenly thought that I was liking that to the quality of her cooking and she was from Mississippi and she took umbrage with that but anyway that's another story student nicknames were there some good nicknames in your outfit oh there were just like any others we had a guy named Frank Strother from Jasper and Frank
was probably one of the uglier individuals that God created, and so we call him the sloth.
He looked like a sloth.
Let's see.
Glenn Honaker from...
Fort Stockton with his short haircut, had white sidewalls and a little short haircut and kind of reddish hair, and somebody said he looked like a lit cigarette.
He never got rid of the nickname, and to this day, I was at the governor's swearing in, and somebody said, cigarette!
I mean, that is his name, so you can't get away from it, even though he hates it.
What was yours?
Once I got into vet school, they called me Doc, and that was probably it, nothing.
Remember one from the freshman year?
No, I don't recall.
I don't think I really had one.
Carl Alexander, some of them called him Kunas or Kuni, which he hated because he was from New Orleans High Society and he was not, in his mind, was not Cajun, was not a Kunas, so he didn't like that.
Let's see, who else?
Were the nicknames a put-down term?
are in effect a kind of a backhanded term of recognition.
Always a term of recognition.
Nicknames are only meaningful in families.
And the core was family.
So no, they were strictly.
And so many people refer to people by their last name.

dropping handles and having upperclassmen call you by your Christian name or your first name was a special thing but in amongst your own class you never referred to anybody by their first name but it was always by the last name and again that was uh that was part of being family and among when you were with some of those old outfit mates are the nicknames still used oh yeah just like uh right there and uh in the rotunda of the capitol somebody else cigarette uh
Joe Weber would be the first member of our class, I guess, to get a star as a brigadier in the Marine Corps.
And somehow he got the name of Joe Buck.
And to this day, I don't care if he's got a star or what.
If I see him, it's Joe Buck.
And it's just the way it is.
Are there some friendships you made that freshman year that have lasted?

I was telling Kyle on the way up here today about how quickly you forget high school, at least I did, and yet the friendships of the Corps, it is truly, I saw two members that I hadn't seen since final review in Austin last month, and it was like yesterday.
And so, yes, they're very deep, lasting friendships.
Politically, they're on different sides of the fence, but both John Sharp and Rick Perry were in my outfit.
And we all, when you live together, you die together.
Chris Roberts runs Federal Land Bank out in Leveland and Brownfield.
I haven't seen Chris in, I guess, since Final Review, and yet I've talked to him on the phone a couple times.
And it's as if it were yesterday.
Deep lasting friendships, there's no question.
Carl Alexander, my freshman roommate second semester, went back to Louisiana.
He really wanted to be part of the LSU scene.
This is where he was raised, what he wanted to do, and to be a cheerleader at LSU.
This is a big social thing, and to be Sigma Chi, and he did it.
And he ended up being a cheerleader and did his fraternity stuff.
but to this day we're still close friends and it's because of our time at A&M.
It's a thing that his dad was class of

46 i think but um it really yeah you bond and it you don't you don't ever forget it uh rick and john were in your outfit in my outfit right describe them as freshmen as you recall both were politicians from the get-go which i i think you find in retrospect find interesting i can remember uh rick
Rick's official lady was a guy named Chico Tuttle, Carl Tuttle.
I don't have any idea what happened to him, but he was gone after our freshman year.
Rick comes in, and the first thing he does is put a picture of a stunning brunette on his dresser.
Turns out it was his older sister, Milla.
But Rick's no fool.
He puts that in.
The upperclassmen come in and say, whoa, who's this?
And it depended on what, you know, what upperclassmen.
If a sophomore, you didn't care.
But if a junior or senior asked, oh, that's my sister, Milla.
And so Rick used Milla as bait.
And quite effectively, a number of the upperclassmen had dates with her.
She's a wonderful lady.
Sharp, same way.
Didn't have a picture of his sister, but always politicking.
Both of them got along well with everyone else.
Did they have nicknames?
Sharp, somebody, we called him Shapp without the R. I was like you from the Lower East Side in Manhattan.
And occasionally, some people call Ricky, Ricky Perry.
Rick, they called him Ricky because he used to dislike it, and so we called him Ricky, but I don't recall any other nicknames.
Both were good, loyal, strong outfit buddies.
Did they get into their share of freshman mischief?
Same as all, we were one for all, all for one.
We had talked about the M-80 story.
I manufactured the M-80s for the outfit.
I've always liked pyrotechnics and had the wherewithal to make.

It takes about 60 to 70 black cat firecrackers to make one M-80, and you've emptied out the gunpowder and put it in an M-80 case and a little waterproof cannon fuse, and you can flush it down anything.
Where did you get the, did you always buy the firecrackers?

I had the stuff, the firecrackers you could buy, in those days you could buy anywhere, and then I bought M-80 cases from a place in Arizona, and cannon fuse you could buy, advertised in a magazine, waterproof cannon fuse.
So that one that John Sharp told me about the guy sitting on the stool reading the bat, you were a...
It was an outfit production, but they were the ones that did it.
What kind of punishment did anybody get as a result of that prank?
I can't, I don't remember.
I don't know if we got caught.
I was going to say, must not...
I don't, the key, there's the right way and the wrong way and the Aggie way.
The key is not to get caught.
Anybody can pull off something and get caught.
No, the key is to not get caught.
I guess back to the sadistic sophomore named Emmons that...
crapped me out the first day I was at A&M.
He was in squadron eight, and he was bad about that to the point that our upperclassmen took him to task a couple times.
But he was bad about using an axe handle and that sort of thing.
He'd gotten onto some of our freshmen.
It was in the spring of our freshman year, and it had hurt one a little bit, and we'd had a lot of problems with him.
So we called in a hit man from squadron 11.
And the guy that came over had one of those tear gas pins.
Emmons lived on the fourth floor, and so we fixed his door so he couldn't get out and lost the tear gas pin under the door.
Well, he was a Marine wannabe and rappelled out of his window, but the rope broke, and he broke his ankles, and that's the last we saw of Mr. Emmons.
